The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, May 03, 2004  LOOSE CHANGE
																								Syndicate Bank has decided to offer 2 per cent subsidy on education loan, a scheme for bright and needy students pursuing higher studies. The subsidy is admissible to all new accounts arranged after March 1, 2004, if the total loan amount does not exceed Rs 4 lakh. The loan is extended to the students whose parents annual income is below Rs 2.5 lakh. 																								Tata AIG General Insurance has unveiled Secured Future Plan, a personal accident policy which assures a fixed monthly income between Rs 10,000 and Rs 35,000 for a period of 5 to 20 years in the event of accidental death, dismemberment and permanent disability of the insured. The insured is offered a choice among two schemes, Silver and Gold. The income is guaranteed over the entire period and is not subject to market risk.																								UTI Mutual Fund has declared a 2 per cent dividend under its scheme for charitable and religious trusts and registered societies and the record date for dividend pay out is May 3, 2004. The net asset value of the unit with a face value of Rs 100 was Rs 101.3 as on April 27, 2004 and the asset under management of the scheme is Rs 364 crore. The scheme has declared a total dividend of 10 per cent in the financial year 2003-04.
